Negative Interest Rate Club
Brussels—Over most of the past decade, central banks have made only limited progress in curbing the powerful global deflationary forces.
Since 2008, the Federal Reserve has maintained interest rates at zero, and has also undertaken unprecedented balance sheet expansions through large-scale bond purchases.
The Bank of England, the Bank of Japan, and the European Central Bank have all followed in the Federal Reserve's footsteps, implementing their own versions of so-called "quantitative easing" (QE).
However, inflation has not been reasonably boosted anywhere.
Despite these countries struggling against deflationary pressures, their monetary policies — as well as their economic performances — are becoming increasingly divergent.
The US and the UK now have growth strong enough to exit expansionary policies and raise interest rates, while the Eurozone and Japan are ramping up QE, further pushing long-term policy interest rates into negative territory.
Why is there this difference?
The short answer is debt.
For decades, the US and the UK have had current account deficits, making them debtor nations, while the Eurozone and Japan have had external surpluses, making them creditor nations.
Negative interest rates benefit debtor nations but harm creditor nations, so the negative interest rate stimulus introduced after the global economic crisis has boosted the recovery of the US and the UK, but had little effect on the Eurozone and Japan.
This is not an isolated phenomenon.
So far, most creditor nations around the world – countries with large and persistent current account surpluses, such as Denmark and Switzerland – have had negative interest rates, not just for long-term government bonds and other "risk-free" debt, but also for medium-term bonds.
This is not a good thing.
Although low interest rates have had little effect, these central banks still adhere to this policy.
If you argue that QE or lowering interest rates cannot bring benefits to the economy, they will brush it off and counter with the concept that raising interest rates can stimulate the economy – which looks unassailable on the surface.
But in reality, this is full of holes.
Even basic economics courses mention the peculiar phenomenon of the "backward-sloping savings supply curve": in certain environments, lowering interest rates lead to increased savings.
This is because lower interest rates reduce the income of savers, causing them to reduce their spending, especially if they have a goal of saving for retirement.
All of this is not to deny the general rule – it is the foundation of modern monetary policy – that lowering interest rates can stimulate consumption and other spending.
The impact is different due to the different debt situations of economic entities.
In a closed economy, each creditor has a debtor, so regardless of what the creditor loses due to extremely low interest rates, the debtor should benefit.
However, in an economy with a large net foreign asset position, creditors are naturally more numerous than debtors.
The situation is exactly the opposite for a country with a large amount of foreign debt.
Therefore, the effects of monetary policies with a lower interest rate limit are different in creditor and debtor economies.
Until recently, this condition was not important because foreign asset positions were often small (measured as a percentage of GDP).
However, today, the foreign asset positions of major industrial economies are large and becoming increasingly diversified, partly due to the leverage that led to the 2007-2008 global financial crisis.
In fact, leverage is still increasing at the national level.
Although current account imbalances have generally eased since the financial crisis, they have not reversed.
This means that surplus countries continue to strengthen their creditor positions, diverging from deficit economies.
Some major commodity exporters, such as Russia and Saudi Arabia, have large current account surpluses when oil prices are high, making them the main exception to the divergence in foreign asset positions.
Since June 2014, the world oil price has plummeted, reversing the wealth trend in these countries.
Their export earnings have declined sharply – many have lost half – forcing them to run deficits and draw on massive sovereign wealth funds accumulated during the global commodity boom.
Now, a significant reduction in spending is unavoidable.
Industrialized economies face completely different challenges.
It's their problem — — in a way, it's a luxury problem — — to ensure that consumers spend the unexpected windfall from falling import prices.
However, in creditor countries, negative interest rates seem not to have promoted this goal; in fact, some external surpluses are even increasing.
This divergence also exists within the eurozone.
Although as a whole, the eurozone is a creditor economy, there are also debtor countries within it.
Debtor countries, such as Spain and Portugal, now have current account surpluses and are gradually reducing their debt.
But the current account surpluses of traditional debtor countries are too high, leading to an increasing debtors' creditors' asymmetry.
The most noteworthy point is that since the financial crisis broke out, Germany's current account surplus has increased to nearly 8% of GDP, meaning that Germany has accumulated more surpluses in this period than in its entire previous history.
According to the current trend, Germany's creditor position may increase from 60% of GDP to 100%.
The central bank governor should be patient.
In fact, economists support the global trend of central bank independence because central bank governors are less eager to stimulate short-term economic growth.
But central bankers seem impatient and are worrying a lot about low inflation, although the output gap is slowly being filled, and the US and Japan have achieved full employment.
Central bankers of debtor nations must stop using more monetary easing that may not be beneficial to production to manipulate the economy.
Instead, they should allow the recovery to develop on its own, even if it is very slow, and wait for the base effect of the falling oil price to disappear.
European Central Bank President Draghi recently admitted that the current monetary policy stance may not be effective in today's global environment.
But promising more of the same is not the solution.
